(332, 13, 'essay', 'What were the reasons for Mussolini‚Äôs rise to power in Italy? How did he deal with the domestic affairs of Italy up to his overthrow?', 20, '- Mussolini rose to power in Italy due to widespread disillusionment after World War I, which left Italy economically weakened and politically unstable. Mussolini capitalized on the fear of socialism and the failure of the democratic government to address issues like unemployment and inflation. He formed the Fascist Party in 1919, promising to restore order and national pride. In 1922, Mussolini staged the \'March on Rome,\' and King Victor Emmanuel III invited him to form a government. Once in power, Mussolini established a dictatorship by dismantling democratic institutions and suppressing political opposition. Domestically, he focused on modernizing Italy‚Äôs economy through state intervention in industries and infrastructure projects like roads and schools. However, he failed to resolve Italy‚Äôs deep economic problems, and his aggressive foreign policies, particularly his alliance with Hitler during World War II, led to his downfall. Mussolini was overthrown in 1943 after Allied forces invaded Italy.', 'This answer traces Mussolini‚Äôs rise to power through manipulation of Italy‚Äôs political unrest and details his efforts and eventual failure in domestic affairs.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(333, 13, 'essay', 'What were Hitler\'s aims in foreign policy? What steps did he take to achieve these aims between 1933 and 1939?', 20, '- Hitler‚Äôs foreign policy was driven by three main aims: overturning the Treaty of Versailles, expanding German territory (Lebensraum), and uniting all ethnic Germans. He sought to reverse the military and territorial restrictions imposed by the Treaty of Versailles. To achieve these aims, Hitler took several aggressive steps: in 1933, he withdrew Germany from the League of Nations; in 1935, he reintroduced conscription and began to rebuild the German military; in 1936, he remilitarized the Rhineland, violating the treaty\'s terms. In 1938, Hitler pursued Anschluss, the union with Austria, incorporating it into the Third Reich. Later that year, through the Munich Agreement, he secured the Sudetenland from Czechoslovakia without facing military opposition. Finally, in 1939, Hitler signed the Nazi-Soviet Non-Aggression Pact with the Soviet Union, securing peace on the Eastern Front and allowing him to invade Poland without fear of Soviet intervention. This invasion led to the outbreak of World War II.', 'This essay details Hitler‚Äôs step-by-step foreign policy actions to achieve his goals of territorial expansion and reversal of the Treaty of Versailles.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(334, 13, 'essay', 'State the aims and organisation of the United Nations Organisation (UNO).', 20, '- The United Nations Organisation (UNO) was founded in 1945 after World War II to promote peace, security, and cooperation among nations. Its main aims include preventing future wars, promoting social progress, protecting human rights, and fostering international cooperation to solve global problems such as poverty and environmental issues. The UNO is organized into six main bodies: the General Assembly, where all member states meet to discuss global issues; the Security Council, responsible for maintaining international peace and security; the International Court of Justice, which settles legal disputes between countries; the Economic and Social Council, which oversees international economic and social cooperation; the Trusteeship Council, which manages trust territories; and the Secretariat, which administers the day-to-day operations of the UN. The Security Council has five permanent members (China, France, Russia, the United Kingdom, and the United States), each with veto power.', 'This essay explains the structure and primary goals of the UN, highlighting its role in promoting peace and international cooperation.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(335, 13, 'essay', 'What justification do the Jews advance for the occupation of Palestine? How have Arab countries responded to the Jewish claims?', 20, '- The Jews justify their occupation of Palestine based on historical and religious ties to the land, which they claim dates back thousands of years. The Balfour Declaration of 1917, in which Britain supported the establishment of a \'national home for the Jewish people\' in Palestine, further strengthened Jewish claims. Additionally, Jews point to the Holocaust as a moral justification for establishing a safe homeland where they could live without fear of persecution. Arab countries, however, have consistently rejected these claims, viewing the establishment of Israel as an illegal occupation of Palestinian land. They argue that the Palestinians, who had been living in the region for centuries, were unjustly displaced. The Arab League has historically supported Palestinian resistance, and several wars have been fought between Israel and its Arab neighbors (e.g., the 1948 Arab-Israeli War, the 1967 Six-Day War) in opposition to Israeli territorial expansion.', 'This essay outlines the competing historical, religious, and political claims over Palestine, as well as the longstanding Arab-Israeli conflict.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(336, 13, 'essay', 'What do you understand by the term \'Cold War\'? Discuss the main events in the development of the Cold War.', 20, '- The term \'Cold War\' refers to the period of intense geopolitical tension between the United States and the Soviet Union from the end of World War II in 1945 until the early 1990s. Unlike a \'hot\' war, the Cold War did not involve direct military conflict between the superpowers but was characterized by political, ideological, and economic rivalry. Key events include the **Truman Doctrine** (1947), in which the U.S. pledged to support countries resisting communism, and the **Marshall Plan**, which aimed to rebuild Europe while containing Soviet influence. The formation of NATO in 1949 and the Warsaw Pact in 1955 solidified the division between East and West. The **Cuban Missile Crisis** in 1962 brought the world to the brink of nuclear war. Other important events include the Korean War (1950-1953), the Vietnam War (1955-1975), and the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979. The Cold War ended with the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991.', 'This essay defines the Cold War and traces its development through key events and conflicts that shaped global politics during the second half of the 20th century.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(337, 13, 'essay', 'What were the reasons for the colonisation of Malawi, Zambia, and Zimbabwe by Britain? Why did Zimbabwe delay to get its independence as compared to Zambia and Malawi?', 20, '- Britain colonized Malawi, Zambia, and Zimbabwe (then Nyasaland, Northern Rhodesia, and Southern Rhodesia) primarily for economic reasons, including access to natural resources like minerals and fertile land. Strategic considerations also played a role, as Britain sought to control the route from the Cape to Cairo, and missionaries advocated for the \'civilizing mission\' of spreading Christianity and Western education. However, Zimbabwe‚Äôs path to independence was delayed compared to Zambia and Malawi due to the settler population, which had established a strong political presence. In 1965, the white minority government of Ian Smith declared unilateral independence from Britain (UDI), leading to a long guerrilla war between the white government and black nationalist forces. Zambia and Malawi, on the other hand, were granted independence more peacefully, in 1964. Zimbabwe only gained independence in 1980 after years of conflict and international pressure.', 'This essay explains the economic and strategic motivations for British colonization and the unique circumstances that delayed Zimbabwe‚Äôs independence.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(338, 13, 'essay', 'State the aims, membership, and organisation of the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA).', 20, '- COMESA (Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa) aims to promote regional integration and economic cooperation among its member states. It seeks to facilitate trade by reducing tariffs, eliminating trade barriers, and establishing a common customs union. COMESA also aims to promote peace and security within the region and improve the living standards of its people through sustainable development. Membership includes 21 countries from Eastern and Southern Africa, including Zambia, Kenya, Uganda, and Zimbabwe. The organization is structured around a council of ministers, a secretariat, and several technical committees responsible for areas like trade, investment, and infrastructure. The secretariat, based in Lusaka, Zambia, coordinates the implementation of COMESA‚Äôs policies.', 'This essay covers the goals, membership, and structure of COMESA, emphasizing its role in fostering regional economic integration and development.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(339, 13, 'essay', 'What challenges did Indira Gandhi face when she took power in India in 1966? What steps did she take to resolve these challenges?', 20, '- Indira Gandhi faced significant economic, political, and social challenges when she assumed power in 1966. Economically, India was suffering from severe food shortages and inflation, largely due to poor harvests and the impact of the Indo-Pakistani War of 1965. Socially, India was grappling with widespread poverty and inequality. Politically, Gandhi had to manage internal divisions within her Congress Party, while externally, tensions with Pakistan persisted. To resolve these challenges, Gandhi implemented the Green Revolution, which introduced high-yielding varieties of crops and improved irrigation, significantly increasing food production. She also nationalized banks in 1969 to ensure better distribution of resources and launched social welfare programs aimed at reducing poverty. In the political sphere, she took steps to centralize power by marginalizing opponents within her party and declared a state of emergency in 1975 to maintain control during a period of political instability. These actions helped stabilize India\'s economy and consolidated her political authority, but the Emergency damaged her democratic credentials.', 'This essay outlines the economic, social, and political challenges Indira Gandhi encountered upon assuming power and describes the measures she took to address these issues, including the Green Revolution and nationalization of banks.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(340, 13, 'essay', 'Explain the challenges faced by China in 1949. How did Mao Zedong attempt to solve them?', 20, '- In 1949, when Mao Zedong and the Communist Party took control of China, the country faced severe challenges. Economically, China was devastated by years of civil war and the Sino-Japanese War, leaving its infrastructure and agriculture in ruins. Inflation was rampant, and food shortages were widespread. Socially, China was deeply divided, with a vast gap between the rural poor and the urban elites, while politically, the new Communist government had to solidify its control and eliminate Nationalist influence. To address these problems, Mao implemented a series of policies aimed at transforming China. Land reforms were introduced, which redistributed land from landlords to peasants, alleviating rural poverty and building support for the Communist regime. Mao also nationalized key industries and initiated the First Five-Year Plan (1953-1957), focused on rapid industrialization, with the Soviet Union providing technical assistance. Mao promoted mass mobilization campaigns like the Great Leap Forward (1958-1962) to increase industrial and agricultural output, though this later led to a catastrophic famine. Politically, Mao‚Äôs government suppressed opposition through campaigns against perceived enemies of the state, consolidating Communist power.', 'This essay discusses the post-civil war challenges China faced under Mao Zedong‚Äôs leadership and the policies he enacted to industrialize the country, redistribute land, and consolidate Communist power.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(341, 13, 'essay', 'Write brief notes on the following topics: The Truman Doctrine, The Marshall Plan, The Cominform, and The Molotov Plan.', 20, 'The Truman Doctrine: Announced in 1947 by U.S. President Harry Truman, it was a policy aimed at containing the spread of communism by providing economic and military aid to countries resisting Soviet influence, particularly Greece and Turkey. The Marshall Plan**: Also known as the European Recovery Program, it was introduced in 1948 by U.S. Secretary of State George Marshall to rebuild war-torn Europe through economic assistance. The goal was to stabilize economies and prevent the spread of communism in Western Europe. - **The Cominform**: Established in 1947, the Communist Information Bureau was an organization that coordinated Communist parties across Europe and aimed to tighten Soviet control over Eastern Bloc countries. It also opposed Western influence in post-war Europe.  - **The Molotov Plan**: In response to the Marshall Plan, the Soviet Union created the Molotov Plan in 1947 to provide economic assistance to Eastern European countries aligned with the USSR. It sought to rebuild and strengthen the economies of socialist states within the Soviet sphere of influence.', 'These brief notes explain key Cold War policies, including the U.S. strategy to contain communism and Soviet efforts to consolidate control over Eastern Europe.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(342, 13, 'essay', 'Describe post-World War Two Japan in the first ten years after the war. What made Japan become an economic world giant after 1960?', 20, '- After World War II, Japan was devastated both physically and economically, with much of its infrastructure destroyed by bombing, including the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki. The Japanese economy was in ruins, and the country faced food shortages and inflation. However, under the leadership of General Douglas MacArthur, the Supreme Commander for the Allied Powers, Japan underwent significant reforms. The U.S. occupation brought democratic changes, including a new constitution in 1947, which established parliamentary democracy and guaranteed civil liberties. Land reforms redistributed land from landlords to tenant farmers, promoting agricultural productivity. After the occupation ended in 1952, Japan began to focus on rebuilding its economy, particularly through industrialization. Japan‚Äôs rapid economic growth after 1960 was fueled by a combination of factors: a highly educated workforce, government policies that promoted industry and exports, and the adoption of advanced technology. The Japanese government also played a key role in directing economic development through strategic investments in infrastructure and technology sectors. Japan‚Äôs focus on manufacturing, particularly in electronics and automobiles, helped it become a global economic powerhouse.', 'This essay explains how Japan recovered from the devastation of World War II through democratic reforms, land redistribution, and a focus on industrialization, eventually becoming an economic giant.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(343, 13, 'essay', 'Write briefly on two of the following: The role of Local Councils, Importance of Informal Employment (Self-Employment), Advantages of Living in a Rural Area Over Living in an Urban Area.', 20, 'The Role of Local Councils: Local councils play a crucial role in managing the day-to-day governance of towns, cities, and rural areas. They are responsible for providing essential services such as waste management, road maintenance, and public health. Councils also facilitate community development projects and ensure local infrastructure is maintained. They serve as a bridge between local populations and national governments, ensuring that local needs are addressed in broader policy decisions. Importance of Informal Employment (Self-Employment): Informal employment, often referred to as self-employment, is critical in many economies, particularly in developing countries where formal job opportunities are limited. It provides a source of income for individuals who might otherwise be unemployed. Informal employment fosters entrepreneurship, allows for flexible working conditions, and often serves as a stepping stone to formal employment. However, it can also lack social protections, such as healthcare and pensions.Advantages of Living in a Rural Area Over Living in an Urban Area: Living in rural areas offers several advantages, including cleaner air, less noise, and a more relaxed pace of life. Housing and land are typically more affordable, and rural areas often have stronger communities with a sense of closeness among residents. In contrast, urban areas can be overcrowded, more expensive, and subject to higher levels of pollution. Rural living also provides easier access to nature and outdoor activities, which can contribute to better mental and physical health.', 'These brief essays highlight the significance of local governance, the importance of informal employment, and the benefits of rural life over urban living.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(344, 14, 'essay', '(a) (i) Explain why most laboratories do not have smooth floors but have rough floors.', 1, '- Rough floors prevent slipping, which improves safety in environments where spills can occur.', 'Rough surfaces provide better traction, which reduces the risk of accidents in the laboratory.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(345, 15, 'essay', '(a) (i) Explain why most laboratories do not have smooth floors but have rough floors.', 1, '- Rough floors prevent slipping, which improves safety in environments where spills can occur.', 'Rough surfaces provide better traction, which reduces the risk of accidents in the laboratory.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(346, 15, 'essay', '(a) (ii) Give two laboratory safety rules to observe when carrying out a titration.', 2, '- Wear protective goggles to prevent splashes from entering your eyes.\n- Ensure all apparatus, including the burette, is clamped securely to avoid spills.', 'Wearing safety goggles and securing equipment minimizes risks during the titration process.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(347, 15, 'essay', '(b) Describe the arrangement of particles in a solid liquid and a gas.', 3, '- In a solid, particles are closely packed in a regular pattern and vibrate in fixed positions.In a liquid, particles are closely packed but can move freely past each other, allowing the liquid to flow and take the shape of its container. In a gas, particles are far apart and move randomly at high speeds.', 'The arrangement of particles in solids results in a definite shape, while in liquids and liquids the particles are free to move and take up the shape of the container they are in.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(348, 15, 'essay', '(c) (i) Explain why solids have higher densities than liquids for the same space occupied.', 1, '- Solids have higher densities because their particles are tightly packed, meaning more mass per unit volume.', 'The compact structure of solid particles leads to greater density compared to liquids.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(349, 15, 'essay', '(c) (ii) Explain why gases are compressible.', 1, '- Gases are compressible because the particles are far apart, allowing them to be pushed closer together under pressure.', 'The large gaps between gas particles make them more compressible compared to liquids and solids.', NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `questions` (`question_id`, `exam_id`, `question_type`, `question_text`, `points`, `correct_answer`, `explanation_text`, `question_order`, `topic`, `grade`) VALUES
(350, 15, 'essay', 'State the four steps in obtaining crystals of copper (II) sulphate (CuSO‚ÇÑ¬∑5H‚ÇÇO) from an aqueous solution of copper (II) sulphate, and give reasons for each step.', 8, '- Step 1: Dissolve copper (II) sulphate in water.\nReason: To form a solution from which crystals can later form.\nStep 2: Heat the solution to evaporate some water.\nReason: To concentrate the solution.\nStep 3: Allow the solution to cool slowly.\nReason: Crystals will form as the solution cools.\nStep 4: Filter and dry the crystals.\nReason: To separate the crystals from the remaining liquid.', 'The process involves concentrating the solution, allowing crystallization, and then separating and drying the crystals.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(351, 15, 'essay', '(a) (i) What is the significant difference between the notations 2N and N‚ÇÇ?', 1, '- 2N refers to two separate nitrogen atoms, while N‚ÇÇ refers to a nitrogen molecule consisting of two nitrogen atoms bonded together.', '2N refers to individual atoms, whereas N‚ÇÇ refers to a bonded nitrogen molecule.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(352, 15, 'essay', '(a) (ii) Describe the dot-and-cross structures showing outer shells only for 2N and N‚ÇÇ.', 1, '- For 2N, each nitrogen atom is represented with five outer electrons (three dots, two crosses) as they are separate atoms. In N‚ÇÇ, the two nitrogen atoms share three pairs of electrons, represented by shared dots and crosses between the atoms to form a triple bond.', 'The dot-and-cross diagram for N‚ÇÇ shows each nitrogen atom sharing three pairs of electrons to achieve a full outer shell through a triple bond.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(353, 15, 'essay', '(b) (i) Compare the electrical conductivity of liquid carbon tetrachloride and liquid potassium chloride.', 1, '- Liquid potassium chloride conducts electricity because it has ions, while liquid carbon tetrachloride does not conduct because it is a covalent compound with no free ions.', 'Ionic compounds like potassium chloride conduct electricity in the liquid state due to the presence of mobile ions, while covalent compounds like carbon tetrachloride do not.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(354, 15, 'essay', '(b) (ii) Which of the two compounds, carbon tetrachloride and potassium chloride, has a higher melting point? Explain your answer.', 2, '- Potassium chloride has a higher melting point because it has strong ionic bonds that require more energy to break compared to the weak Van der Waals forces in carbon tetrachloride.', 'Ionic compounds have higher melting points due to the strength of the electrostatic forces between ions, whereas covalent compounds have weaker intermolecular forces.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(355, 15, 'essay', '(a) (i) Write the word equation for the reaction between magnesium and hydrochloric acid.', 1, '- Magnesium + Hydrochloric acid ‚Üí Magnesium chloride + Hydrogen', 'This is a simple word equation showing the reaction between a metal and an acid, producing a salt and hydrogen gas.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(356, 15, 'essay', '(a) (ii) What is the chemical test for hydrogen gas?', 1, '- The test for hydrogen gas is inserting a lit splint into the gas, which will cause a \'pop\' sound if hydrogen is present.', 'Hydrogen gas is flammable and burns with a characteristic \'pop\' when ignited.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(357, 15, 'essay', '(b) (i) Calculate the mass of magnesium that was in excess, given that 0.03 g of magnesium was used with 20 cm¬≥ of 0.10 mol/dm¬≥ hydrochloric acid.', 4, '', 'The calculation involves finding the amount of magnesium that reacts with the hydrochloric acid and determining the excess.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(358, 15, 'essay', '(b) (ii) Calculate the volume of hydrogen gas produced at room temperature and pressure (r.t.p).', 2, '', 'The volume of hydrogen gas can be calculated using the molar volume of a gas at r.t.p.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(359, 15, 'essay', '(a) Use the Periodic Table to state: (i) The name of the element with electronic configuration 2,8,18,7.', 1, '- The element is chlorine.', 'The electronic configuration 2,8,18,7 corresponds to chlorine, a halogen in Group VII.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(360, 15, 'essay', '(a) (ii) Use the Periodic Table to state: The chemical symbol of the element that forms an acidic oxide with the formula XO‚ÇÇ as its only oxide.', 1, '- The element is carbon, and the oxide is carbon dioxide (CO‚ÇÇ).', 'Carbon forms carbon dioxide, an acidic oxide commonly found in the atmosphere.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(361, 15, 'essay', '(a) (iii) Use the Periodic Table to state: The name of the most electronegative halogen.', 1, '- The most electronegative halogen is fluorine.', 'Fluorine is the most electronegative element in the Periodic Table, making it highly reactive.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(362, 15, 'essay', '(a) (iv) Use the Periodic Table to state: The name of the elements in Group V.', 1, '- The elements in Group V of the Periodic Table are nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), arsenic (As), antimony (Sb), and bismuth (Bi).', 'Group V elements, also known as the nitrogen group, display a range of properties. Nitrogen (N) and phosphorus (P) are non-metals, while arsenic (As) and antimony (Sb) are metalloids, and bismuth (Bi) is a metal. These elements typically form compounds with a -3 oxidation state, though they can exhibit multiple oxidation states. They are crucial in various biological and industrial processes; for example, nitrogen is essential for life and is a major component of the atmosphere, while phosphorus is key in fertilizers and DNA structure.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(363, 15, 'essay', '(a) (v) Use the Periodic Table to state: The number of metals in Group I.', 1, '- There are six metals in Group I.', 'Group I contains the alkali metals, including lithium, sodium, potassium, rubidium, cesium, and francium.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(364, 15, 'essay', '(b) Elements A, B, C, D, and E are arranged in order of their increasing atomic numbers. If element C is a noble gas, state: (i) The formulae of the ions formed by B and E.', 2, '- B forms B‚Å∫ and E forms E¬≤‚Åª.', 'In this scenario, B is likely a metal forming a positive ion (B‚Å∫), and E is likely a non-metal forming a negative ion (E¬≤‚Åª), following trends in atomic number and ion formation.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(365, 15, 'essay', '(b) (ii) State the only noble gas that cannot be C from the previous question.', 1, '- Helium (He) cannot be C.', 'Helium cannot be element C because it only has two electrons and does not fit the properties of a noble gas higher in atomic number, like Argon or Neon.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(366, 15, 'essay', 'Choose from the list of oxides given below to answer the questions that follow. An oxide may be chosen once, more than once, or not at all. Al‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ, CaO, CO‚ÇÇ, CO, Fe‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ, H‚ÇÇO, ZnO. (a) Which two oxides are amphoteric?', 1, '- Al‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ and ZnO are amphoteric.', 'Amphoteric oxides can act as both acids and bases. Aluminium oxide (Al‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ) and zinc oxide (ZnO) exhibit this behavior.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(367, 15, 'essay', '(b) From these,  Al‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ, CaO, CO‚ÇÇ, CO, Fe‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ, H‚ÇÇO, ZnO, Which two oxides are neutral?', 1, '- CO and H‚ÇÇO are neutral.', 'Neutral oxides, such as carbon monoxide (CO) and water (H‚ÇÇO), do not form acids or bases when reacting with water.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(368, 15, 'essay', '(c) State the other two types of oxides and give an example of each type. (i) Type 1:', 1, '- Basic oxide. Example: CaO (Calcium oxide).', 'Basic oxides react with acids to form salts and water. Calcium oxide (CaO) is a typical example of a basic oxide.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(369, 15, 'essay', '(c) (ii)  State the other two types of oxides and give an example of each type. (ii)Type 2:', 1, '- Acidic oxide. Example: CO‚ÇÇ (Carbon dioxide).', 'Acidic oxides react with bases to form salts and water. Carbon dioxide (CO‚ÇÇ) is a common acidic oxide.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(370, 15, 'essay', 'Zinc is extracted from its sulphide ore, zinc blende, in a blast furnace at 1400¬∞C. (a) What reducing agent is used in the extraction of zinc in this furnace?', 1, '- Carbon (C) is the reducing agent.', 'Carbon is commonly used as a reducing agent to extract zinc by reducing zinc oxide (ZnO) in the blast furnace.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(371, 15, 'essay', '(b) Name another ore from which zinc can be extracted.', 1, '- Calamine (ZnCO‚ÇÉ).', 'Calamine, or zinc carbonate (ZnCO‚ÇÉ), is another common ore of zinc, used in extraction processes.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(372, 15, 'essay', '(c) Write a balanced chemical equation for the reaction that occurs when zinc blende is roasted in air.', 1, '- 2ZnS + 3O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí 2ZnO + 2SO‚ÇÇ.', 'Zinc sulfide (ZnS) reacts with oxygen to form zinc oxide (ZnO) and sulfur dioxide (SO‚ÇÇ) during roasting.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(373, 15, 'essay', '(d) Name a pollutant gas produced when zinc blende is roasted in air.', 1, '- Sulfur dioxide (SO‚ÇÇ).', 'Sulfur dioxide (SO‚ÇÇ) is a major pollutant produced when zinc sulfide is roasted, contributing to acid rain.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(374, 15, 'essay', '(e) Describe how the pollutant produced in the extraction of zinc is converted into a useful product in industry.', 3, '- Sulfur dioxide (SO‚ÇÇ) is converted into sulfuric acid (H‚ÇÇSO‚ÇÑ) through the contact process. First, SO‚ÇÇ is oxidized to sulfur trioxide (SO‚ÇÉ) using a vanadium pentoxide (V‚ÇÇO‚ÇÖ) catalyst. Then, the SO‚ÇÉ is absorbed in water to form sulfuric acid.', 'In industry, sulfur dioxide (SO‚ÇÇ) is utilized to produce sulfuric acid, a valuable industrial chemical, via the contact process.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(375, 15, 'essay', '(f) (i) Name an element that is alloyed with zinc to form brass.', 1, '- Copper (Cu).', 'Brass is an alloy made by combining copper (Cu) and zinc (Zn).', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(376, 16, 'essay', '(a) (i) Explain why most laboratories do not have smooth floors but have rough floors.', 1, '- Rough floors prevent slipping, which improves safety in environments where spills can occur.', 'Rough surfaces provide better traction, which reduces the risk of accidents in the laboratory.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(377, 16, 'essay', '(a) (ii) Give two laboratory safety rules to observe when carrying out a titration.', 2, '- Wear protective goggles to prevent splashes from entering your eyes.\n- Ensure all apparatus, including the burette, is clamped securely to avoid spills.', 'Wearing safety goggles and securing equipment minimizes risks during the titration process.', NULL, NULL, NULL),
